Russian communism is back
Moscow – many years ago, during my sabbatical from teaching at an American university, I returned to my hometown of Moscow.
My destination was not some haven of free speech.
But there was still some freedom left here once.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny had once toured the country in an effort to garner support for politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Popular protests have erupted.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely seen as a relic of the past.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and his protest movement has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation has been banned for "extremism," and its members are either exiled or under investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights activists, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agents" list – or worse – labeled as "undesirable individuals."
Over the past year, Russia has descended into a non-free state, though not far-off, but extremely intense.
For example, in 2012, a law was enacted designating foreign agents, with the goal of destroying or discrediting institutions or individuals engaging in "political activity" and receiving funding from abroad.
However, the law's application has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where sharing a tweet can now be grounds for being labeled a foreign agent.
("Undesirable" label will lead to complete suppression.
) This year alone, a record 101 entities were added to the list of foreign agents.
The total of 359 includes 88 media-related institutions and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the above "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of news and propaganda work is, of course, to influence politics.
But this is exactly the problem: despite President Vladimir Putin having positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he sees criticism as a survival threat.
Despite all the silence and persecution, it was the Communist Party, an unlikely group, that survived and became the only true opposition to the Kremlin.
This was largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy – urging the public to support forces that were most likely to defeat Kremlin-backed candidates – and the Communist Party performed strongly in the parliamentary and regional elections last month.
Official data showed that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the State Duma (parliament) votes, while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party obtained nearly 49.8%.
However, the Communists refused to acknowledge the results, insisting that the vote had been rigged.
Actually, some experts estimate that they should have received around 30% of the votes, while the United Russia party should have received around 35%.
For many Russians, Communists seem more respected now than Putin.
But they are not the original Communists.
They not only do not deny the pleasures of the world, but party members instead wear fur coats, are enthusiastic about traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some of them are billionaires — such as the charismatic agricultural manager Pavel Grudinin (who was barred from participating in last month's election).
Despite being led by 77-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, the party is increasingly influenced and supported by young members.
For example, Nikolai Bondarik.
Bondarik, known as the "red Navalny," criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018 at the age of 36.
Recently, when a regional minister said that Russians should be able to live better on a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (around $50), Bondarik recorded his efforts to prove the minister wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with prohibition from running, Bondarik was still allowed to participate in the parliamentary elections last month.
Although he received support from Navalny's "wise vote" system, he still lost to the candidates of the United Russia Party.
But his potential should not be ignored: he recently came up with a slogan for a protest, accusing "the state and government" of taking over United Russia.
And then there's 43-year-old Anastasia Yudina.
Like Bondarenko, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she is still very — and increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the "wise vote" system, another rising star, elegant Yekaterina Engovatova, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the modernization of the Communist Party reflects people's longing for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the ideal society they envisioned was strict, it was still characterized by justice and kindness.
Furthermore, just like liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which an individual's eccentricity will not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all Kremlin opponents are increasingly joining forces: forming the "United Russia" that can counter Putin's United Russia Party.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babis – also known as the Czech Donald Trump – failed to be re-elected as prime minister because the opposition alliance put aside their ideological differences and formed a united alliance, led by Petr Fiala, who may also lead a new government alongside another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
Hungary's opposition will also present a unified election list in next year's parliamentary elections and nominate a unified candidate for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still has a democratic system, so Babis is preparing to join the opposition forces.
However, toppling Putin will be much harder, and it's not difficult to predict that there will be more measures aimed at dismantling the Communist Party.
But this approach has also brought risks to the Kremlin.
Now, the situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not died out," and points to the country's "active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he at least still has an interest in pretending that Russia is not heading towards near-authoritarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia towards an even more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin treats Russian liberals as it has in the past, repeatedly and capriciously making and enforcing rules, driving the Communist Party underground, then social explosion is even more likely to happen.
But if it decides not to suppress them anymore, Russian Communists – yes, Communists – could become a force to be reckoned with.
